{{Infobox book | name = The Institutes of Biblical Law | image = File:The Institutes of Biblical Law.jpg | caption = Cover | author = [[Rousas Rushdoony|Rousas John Rushdoony]] | country = United States | language = English | subject = [[Theonomy]] | publisher = The Craig Press | pub_date = 1973 | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover]]) | pages = 890 | isbn = 978-0875524108 | dewey= | congress= | oclc= }}
'''''The Institutes of Biblical Law''''' is a 1973 book by the philosopher and theologian [[Rousas Rushdoony|Rousas John Rushdoony]]. It is the first volume of a three-volume work, also referred to by the same title, which is modeled after [[John Calvin]]'s ''[[Institutes of the Christian Religion]]'' (1536). Together with Rushdoony's other writings, the book is the basis of [[Christian Reconstructionism]].
==Summary== Rushdoony expounds the [[Ten Commandments]], adopting a [[Theonomy|theonomic]] perspective. He maintains that almost all of the Old Testament civil law is normative for civil governments.<ref name="Frame">{{cite journal|last=Frame|first=John|author-link=John Frame (theologian)|title=The Institutes of Biblical Law: A Review Article|journal=[[Westminster Theological Journal|WTJ]]|year=1976|volume=38|issue=2|pages=200–201|url=http://www.frame-poythress.org/frame_articles/1976Rushdoony.htm|accessdate=22 January 2012}}</ref> Rushdoony provides an outline of a program for establishing a Christian [[theocracy]].<ref name=Chapman>{{cite book |title=Culture Wars: An Encyclopedia of Issues, Viewpoints, and Voices, Volume 1 |last=Chapman |first=Roger |authorlink= |author2=Waskey, Andrew J. |year=2009 |publisher=M.E.Sharpe |location= |isbn=978-0765617613 |page=90 |pages= |url= }}</ref>
==Reception==
The theologian [[John Frame (theologian)|John Frame]] gave ''The Institutes of Biblical Law'' a mixed review in ''[[Westminster Theological Journal]]'', writing that the book convinced him that "Rushdoony is one of the most important Christian social critics alive today", but also criticizing it on various grounds. Frame credited Rushdoony with cogently arguing against attempts to replace scripture with [[natural law]], with showing a broad and deep knowledge of scripture, and with "a remarkably detailed grasp of the historical background and present condition of human culture." However, he found the book "a bit rough-hewn", noting that it "began as a series of lectures" and in some respects still resembles one, and that it contained "considerable repetition". Overall, Frame concluded that the book had "great strengths and great weaknesses", noting that he had tried "to keep this review balanced between strong praise and strong criticism."<ref name="Frame" />
The journalist [[M. Stanton Evans]], writing in the ''[[National Review]]'', described ''The Institutes of Biblical Law'' as "a work of prodigious scope and erudition" and a "thoughtful book".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Evans|first=M. Stanton|title=Dark Horses|journal=[[National Review]]|year=1978|volume=30|issue=1|page=45}}{{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}</ref> [[Joe Bageant]] suggests that if the United States experiences a [[Fourth Great Awakening|fourth]] "[[Great Awakening]]", historians may one day "document it as beginning in 1973 with the publication of R. J. Rushdoony's seminal ''The Institutes of Biblical Law''."<ref>{{cite book|last=Bageant|first=Joe|author-link=Joe Bageant|title=Deer Hunting with Jesus: Dispatches from America's Class War|year=2007|page=189}}</ref> Peter Montgomery of the ''[[Public Eye Magazine]]'' describes ''The Institutes of Biblical Law'' as Rushdoony's "magnum opus", and identifies it and Rushdoony's other writings as providing the basis for Christian Reconstructionism.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Montgomery|first=Peter|title=Biblical Economics: The Divine Laissez-Faire Mandate|journal=[[Public Eye Magazine]]|year=2015|pages=11–15}}{{subscription needed|via=[https://www.ebsco.com EBSCO]'s Academic Search Complete}}</ref>
